2–Male":"1132–Overleden","1162–Female":"1162–Overleden","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1162":"1162","Walcott, Norfolk, , England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1144–1235":"1144–1235","1146–Female":"1146–Deceased","1176–1267":"1176–1267","1132–Male":"1132–Deceased","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1162":"1162","Walcott, Norfolk, , England":"Walcott, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walcot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Walcott  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walcott","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Walcott, Walcot, or Walcote, for example in Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Norfolk, Oxfordshire, and Wiltshire, all named in Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’ (plural <i>cotu</i>), i.e. ‘the cottage where the (Welsh-speaking) Britons lived’. This name is also frequent in Barbados and Jamaica, when emancipated slaves adopted it from the name of one or other of the sugar plantations owned there by English families called Walcott.","History: This surname was in MA from an early date. William Walcott emigrated from England to Salem, MA, in 1637; John Wolcott (1632–1690) is recorded in Springfield, MA."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Walcot was born in 1144, in Walcott, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Rhys of Deheubarth, was 12 and his mother, Jane, was -18. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. David Walcot. He died in 1235, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1144–1235":"1144–1235","1146–Female":"1146–Surnud","1176–1267":"1176–1267","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1162":"1162","Walcott, Norfolk, , England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1144–1235":"1144–1235","1146–Female":"1146–Kuollut","1176–1267":"1176–1267","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1162":"1162","Walcott, Norfolk, , England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1144–1235":"1144–1235","1146–Female":"1146–Décédée","1176–1267":"1176–1267","1132–Male":"1132–Décédé","1162–Female":"1162–Décédée","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1162":"1162","Walcott, Norfolk, , England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque David Walcot est né en 1144, à Walcott, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Lord Rhys of Deheubarth, avait 12 ans et sa mère, Jane, avait -18 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. David Walcot. Il est décédé en 1235, à l’âge de 91 ans."},"de":{"1144–1235":"11